Part II - (Loan Data from Prosper)¶

by (Edward Obi-Rapu)¶

Dataset Overview¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate),current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Investigation Overview¶

We would be exploring the dataset to observe the various relationships that exist with focus on factors that afffect the Loan Status.

#Columns with the string 'number' are supposed to be string type column as they reflect id and computation are not to be preformed on them

#Columns with the string 'data' are supposed to be date time type column as they reflect date and time; and should be change to appropriate correction

column_head = data.columns.values
for col  in column_head:
    if "Number"  in col:
        data[col] = data[col].astype(str)
    if 'Date' in col:
        data[col] = pd.to_datetime(data[col])

#Function called <b>'barh_plot'</b> that will collect two variable (Column, and y_label). It will plot horizontal bar plot with the column provide expressing values in percentage.
def barh_plot(column, y_label):
    data[column].value_counts(sort=False, normalize=True).sort_index(ascending=False).mul(100).round(1).plot(kind='barh')
    plt.xlabel('Percentage')
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.title('Distribution by ' + y_label)

    plt.grid(b=True, which='both', color='g', linestyle='-', axis = 'x')
In [31]:
#Function called <b>'pie_plot'</b> that will collect two variable (Column, and Label).
#It will plot Pie Chart with the column provide expressing values in percentage.
def pie_plot(column, label):
    data[column].value_counts(sort=False, normalize=True).sort_index(ascending=False).mul(100).round(1).plot(kind='pie')
    plt.title('Distribution by ' + label)

# Function called <b>'histogram_plot'</b> that will collect two variable (Column, and Label).
#It will Histogram with the column provide expressing values in counts.
def histogram_plot(column, label) :
    sns.histplot(data[column],
        bins=25,  kde=True,
        fill=True
                )

    plt.title('Histogram of ' + label)

(Visualization 1)¶

We start by examining the mean values of the borrower APR after grouping the data by term and Loan Status.

In [50]:
def cat_mean(var_1, var_2, var_3):
    cat_means = data.groupby([var_1, var_2]).mean()[var_3]
    cat_means = cat_means.reset_index(name = 'num_var2_avg')
    cat_means = cat_means.pivot(index = var_2, columns = var_1,
                                values = 'num_var2_avg')
    
    sns.heatmap(cat_means, annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
               cbar_kws = {'label' : f'mean({var_3})'});
In [51]:
cat_mean('Term', 'LoanStatus', 'BorrowerAPR')
plt.title('Mean Borrower APR by Loan Status and Term'.title(),
               fontsize = 14, weight = "bold");

Observation from the above plot is quite profound:

  1. we observe the positive correlation between the Borrower APR and the Loan Status Past Due for the 36 and 60 term. we can infer that the higher the borrower APR the higher the tendency for the Loan to be past due date by a significat amount.
  2. From those that where charged off, Completed, current, defaulted or in final payment that show a positive increase in the Borrower APR with increase in the term.

(Visualization 2)¶

We start by examining the mean values of the borrower APR after grouping the data by Income range and Loan Status

In [52]:
cat_mean('IncomeRange', 'LoanStatus', 'BorrowerAPR')
plt.title('Mean Borrower APR by Loan Status and Income Range'.title(),
               fontsize = 14, weight = "bold");

Observation from the above plot is quite profound:

  1. For the 'Not Employed' column that those with a higher Borrower APR completed their Loan payment as compared with those with lower Borrower APR that were charged off.
  2. For loan pass their due date by over 120 days, we observe that their Borrower APR are within the range of 0.27 to 0.28.
  3. All those who were passed their due date for repayment had Borrower APR above 0.2

  3. The not employed either completed their payment or the loan were charged off. 0.2

Observations¶

For the above visualizations, We have a strong dependency of loan status on a number of factors such as the Higher the Borrower APR the higher the tendency for default on payment or for payment to be past its due date.

For the original amount of loan issued, it was observed to be dependent on a number of factors such as Income range of said individual, Employment Status and the number of months assign as repay plan. It was also observed of the lack of relationship better the amount of loan issued to the debit to income ratio of said individual.

For the Borrowers APR, we observed an inverse relationship mean for increase in Loan origninal amount and monthly require repayment amount; a decrease in the borrower APR we observed.
